The '''Cultural Zones of India''' are seven overlapping zones defined by the [[Ministry of Culture (India)|Ministry of Culture]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indiaculture.nic.in/indiaculture/index.asp|title=Zonal Cultural Centers|publisher=[[Ministry of Culture (India)|Ministry of Culture]]|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110808091005/http://www.indiaculture.nic.in/indiaculture/index.asp|archivedate=2011-08-08|df=}}</ref> of the [[Government of India]] to promote and preserve the [[cultural heritage]] of various regions of [[India]].<ref name="wzccsite">{{Citation | title=West Zone Culture Center | publisher=West Zone Culture Centre | accessdate=2010-12-15 | url=http://www.wzccindia.com/ | quote=''... West Zone Cultural Centre (WZCC) with its headquarters at Udaipur is one of the seven Zonal Cultural Centres set up during 1986-87, under the direct initiative of the Ministry of Human Resource Development, Govt. of India ...''}}</ref> Each of these zones has been provided with a zonal centre.<ref name="szccsite">{{Citation | title=South Zone Culture Center: Other Zones | publisher=South Zone Culture Centre | accessdate=2010-12-15 | url=http://www.szcc.tn.nic.in/ | quote=''... North East Zone Cultural Centre - Nagaland - Assam, Tripura, Manipur, Arunachal Pradesh, Nagaland & Meghalaya ...''}}</ref> Most zonal centres were announced by the then-[[Prime Minister of India]], [[Rajiv Gandhi]], in 1985 and formally began functioning in the 1986-87 period. Their stated goal is "''to strengthen the ancient roots of Indian culture and evolve and enrich composite national culture''".<ref name="nzccsite">{{Citation | title=North Zone Culture Center | publisher=North Zone Culture Centre | accessdate=2010-12-15 | url=http://www.culturenorthindia.com/ | quote=''... Rajiv Gandhi inaugurated the North Zone Cultural Center on 6th Nov. 1985 the then Prime Minister of India ... one of the seven cultural centers established in the country to strengthen the ancient roots of Indian Culture and evolve and enrich composite National Culture ... Punjab, Haryana, Himachal Pradesh, Jammu & Kashmir, Uttrakhand, Rajasthan & Chandigarh (U.T.) ...''}}</ref>
The city of [[Kolkata]], formerly the capital of [[British India]] and [[West Bengal]], is also known as the "Cultural Capital of India."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kolkata.citydetails.in/city-guide-leftmenu-117/359-kolkata-the-cultural-capital-of-india.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-04-25 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203002244/https://kolkata.citydetails.in/city-guide-leftmenu-117/359-kolkata-the-cultural-capital-of-india.html |archivedate=2013-12-03 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Pielou|first=Adrianne|title=India: Calcutta, the capital of culture|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/luxury/travel/1245/india-calcutta-the-capital-of-culture.html|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=March 4, 2011}}</ref>
==The zones==
Each zone has a zonal headquarters where a zonal cultural center has been established.<ref name="szccsite"/> Several [[States of India|states]] have membership in multiple zones, but no state subdivisions are utilized in the zonal divisions. In addition to promoting the culture of the zones they are responsible for, each zonal center also works to cross-promote and create exposure to other cultural zones of India by organizing functions and inviting artistes from other zones.
