==Estonia== {{Further|Languages of Estonia}} According to the [[2011 Estonia Census|2011 Population and Housing Census (PHC 2011)]] 157 (up from 109 in 2000) different languages are spoken as native language in [[Estonia]]. Of those 25 have more than 100 speakers.<ref name="Estonian PHC2011">[http://www.stat.ee/64629?parent_id=39113 PHC 2011: 157 native languages spoken in Estonia]</ref>
Estonian is the official language of Estonia and 886,859 or 68.5% of permanent residents spoke it as native language.<ref name="Estonian PHC2011"/> Russian is spoken by 383,062 (29.6%), Ukrainian by 8,012 (0.6%), Finnish by 2,617 (0.17%) and Belorussian by 1,663 (0.13%). Other languages have less than thousand speakers.
==Faroe Islands== {{Further|Languages of Denmark}} There are two official languages in the Faroe Islands, [[Danish language|Danish]] and [[Faroese language|Faroese]].<ref>https://snl.no/F%C3%A6r%C3%B8yene</ref> According to the public census [[Hagstova Føroya]] in 2014, more than 90 percent had Faroese as their first language.<ref>http://aktuelt.fo/filipinskt+er+5storsta+mal+i+foroyum.html</ref> The entire list of spoken languages in 2014 is:<ref>http://www.hagstova.fo/fo/folkateljing/folkid-111111/filipinsk-og-teilenskt-vunnu-fram-sum-modurmal</ref>
