==Syria== [[Modern Standard Arabic|Arabic]] is an [[official language]] of Syria. Several modern [[Varieties of Arabic|Arabic dialects]] are used in everyday life, most notably [[Levantine Arabic|Levantine]] in the west and [[Mesopotamian Arabic|Mesopotamian]] in the northeast. [[Kurdish language|Kurdish]] (in its [[Kurmanji]] form) is widely spoken in the [[Kurdish people|Kurdish]] regions of Syria. [[Armenian language|Armenian]] and [[Turkish language|Turkish]] ([[South Azeri language|South Azeri]] dialect) are spoken among the [[Armenians|Armenian]] and [[Syrian Turkmen|Turkmen]] minorities.
[[Aramaic language|Aramaic]] was the [[lingua franca]] of the region before the advent of [[Classical Arabic|Arabic]], and it is still spoken among [[Assyrian people|Assyrians]], and [[Syriac language|Classical Syriac]] still used as the liturgical language of [[Syriac Christianity|various Syriac Christian denominations]]. Most remarkably, [[Western Neo-Aramaic]] is still spoken in the village of [[Ma'loula]] as well as two neighboring villages, 35 miles (56&nbsp;km) northeast of Damascus. Many educated Syrians also speak English and French languages.
