==Turkmenistan== People in Turkmenistan (when it was still a part of the [[Russian Empire]]) were enumerated by native tongue [[1897 census|in the 1897 Russian Empire Census]].{{citation needed|date=July 2014}} In addition to the Soviet Union enumerating people by ethnicity for its entire existence,{{citation needed|date=July 2014}} [[Turkmenistan]] also enumerated people by ethnicity in its only post-Soviet census in 1995.<ref>https://www.state.gov/documents/organization/171762.pdf</ref>
==Ukraine== [[File:UkraineNativeLanguagesCensus2001detailed-en.png|right|thumb|250px|Ethnolinguistic composition of Ukraine.]] {{see also|Censuses in Ukraine|Legislation on languages in Ukraine|Languages of Ukraine}} People in Ukraine (when it was still a part of the [[Russian Empire]]) were enumerated by native tongue [[1897 census|in the 1897 Russian Empire Census]].<ref>[http://www.ahsgr.org/Researchlibrary/Holdings/Russian%20National%20Census%20of%201897.pdf Thomas K. Edlund. The Russian National Census of 1897]</ref> In addition to the Soviet Union enumerating people by ethnicity for its entire existence,<ref>{{cite book|last=Grenoble|first=L.A.|title=Language Policy in the Soviet Union|series=Language Policy|year=2003|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=9781402012983|page=27}}</ref> [[Ukraine]] also enumerated people by ethnicity and native language in its only post-Soviet census in 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-stat.mashke.org/ukraine-ethnic2001.htm |title=Ethnic composition of Ukraine 2001 |publisher=Pop-stat.mashke.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref>
